VALUES
(
  'Growing Tomatoes: Complete Guide',
  'Step-by-step guide to planting, watering, nurturing, and harvesting tomatoes in South African conditions.',
  'Crops', 'beginner',
  E'Tomatoes are one of the most rewarding vegetables to grow in South Africa. With the right steps, a single plant can produce 4–8 kg of fruit per season.\n\nBEST PLANTING SEASONS\nSummer rainfall regions (Gauteng, Limpopo, Mpumalanga): Plant September–November\nWinter rainfall regions (Western Cape): Plant February–April\nCoastal regions (KZN, Eastern Cape): Year-round with some shelter in winter\n\nSOIL PREPARATION\n1. Choose a sunny spot that receives at least 6–8 hours of direct sunlight daily\n2. Dig the soil to 30–40 cm deep and remove all stones, weeds, and old roots\n3. Mix in 2–3 buckets of well-rotted compost per square metre\n4. Add 100g of superphosphate fertilizer per square metre and work it in\n5. Test soil pH — tomatoes prefer pH 6.0–6.8. Add lime if too acidic\n6. Rake the bed smooth and let it rest for 1 week before planting\n\nSTEP-BY-STEP PLANTING\n1. Start seeds indoors in seed trays 6–8 weeks before transplanting\n2. Fill trays with seedling mix, sow seeds 5mm deep, 2 seeds per cell\n3. Water gently and cover with plastic until germination (7–10 days at 20–25°C)\n4. Once seedlings have 2 true leaves, thin to 1 seedling per cell\n5. Harden off seedlings: place outside in shade for 3–4 days, then full sun\n6. Transplant outdoors when seedlings are 15–20 cm tall and frost risk is past\n7. Dig holes 60 cm apart in rows 80 cm apart\n8. Plant deep — bury up to the lowest set of leaves to encourage strong roots\n9. Water well immediately after planting\n10. Place a sturdy stake 1.5 m tall beside each plant and tie loosely with soft string\n\nWATERING SCHEDULE\nWeeks 1–2 after transplant: Water every day — the plant is establishing roots\nWeeks 3 onwards: Water deeply every 2–3 days (more in hot weather)\nRule: Stick your finger 5 cm into soil — if dry, water now\nAmount: 5–10 litres per plant per watering — water slowly at the base\nCritical: Keep watering consistent — irregular watering causes blossom end rot and cracked fruit\nAvoid: Never water the leaves — keep foliage dry to prevent fungal disease\nDrip irrigation or soaker hose at soil level is ideal\n\nNURTURING YOUR PLANTS\nWeek 2: Apply a layer of mulch (straw or dry grass) 5–8 cm thick around each plant to retain moisture and suppress weeds\nWeek 3: Begin side-dressing with compost tea or a balanced fertilizer (3:1:5 or 2:3:4) every 2 weeks\nWeek 4 onwards: Remove suckers — the shoots that grow between the main stem and a branch. This directs energy to fruit production\nEvery week: Tie the main stem to the stake as it grows — use soft ties, not wire\nEvery week: Check for yellowing lower leaves — remove them to improve airflow\n\nFERTILIZING PLAN\nAt planting: Superphosphate (supports root development)\nWeeks 3–6 (before flowering): High-nitrogen fertilizer like LAN (Limestone Ammonium Nitrate) — promotes leafy growth\nFrom flowering onwards: Switch to low-nitrogen, high-potassium fertilizer (3:1:5) — promotes fruit set and quality\nDo NOT over-fertilize with nitrogen after flowering — this creates lush leaves but poor fruit\n\nPEST AND DISEASE WATCH\n• Red spider mite: Yellowing, stippled leaves — spray neem oil or miticide\n• Hornworm caterpillar: Large holes in leaves, green caterpillars — hand-pick or spray Bt (Bacillus thuringiensis)\n• Early blight: Brown spots with yellow rings on lower leaves — remove affected leaves, spray copper fungicide\n• Fusarium wilt: Yellowing and wilting despite good water — no cure, remove plant and don''t plant tomatoes there for 3 years\n• Whitefly: Clouds of tiny white insects — use yellow sticky traps or spray insecticidal soap\n\nHARVESTING\nTomatoes are ready 60–80 days after transplanting, depending on the variety\n\nSigns of ripeness:\n• Skin turns from green to red (or yellow/orange depending on variety)\n• Fruit feels slightly soft when gently squeezed\n• Fruit separates easily from the stem with a slight twist\n\nHow to harvest:\n1. Pick in the morning when it is cool\n2. Twist and pull gently — do not yank or the stem can break the plant\n3. If fruit splits on the plant, harvest immediately\n4. Green tomatoes can ripen indoors at room temperature — never in the fridge\n\nSTORAGE\n• Room temperature: Ripe tomatoes keep for 5–7 days on the counter\n• Never refrigerate — cold destroys flavour and texture\n• Overripe fruit: Cook immediately, freeze as sauce, or dry in the sun\n• For selling: Harvest slightly underripe for market, they ripen during transport',
  45, 'en', true
),
(
  'Growing Spinach: Complete Guide',
  'How to plant, water, feed, and harvest spinach for a continuous supply throughout the year.',
  'Crops', 'beginner',
  E'Spinach is one of the fastest and easiest vegetables to grow, providing nutritious harvests within 6–8 weeks. It thrives in cool conditions and tolerates light frost.\n\nBEST PLANTING SEASONS\nAll regions: February–April (autumn) and July–September (late winter/spring)\nCool highland areas (Drakensberg, highveld): Can grow year-round in summer with shade cloth\nAvoid planting in midsummer heat — spinach bolts (goes to seed) rapidly above 25°C\n\nSOIL PREPARATION\n1. Choose a partially shaded spot or one with afternoon shade in summer\n2. Dig the bed to 20–25 cm deep\n3. Add 2 buckets of compost per square metre and fork it in thoroughly\n4. Spinach needs rich, nitrogen-heavy soil — add 60g of 2:3:2 fertilizer per square metre\n5. Aim for pH 6.5–7.0 — add lime if soil is acidic\n6. Ensure good drainage — spinach roots rot in waterlogged soil\n7. Rake smooth and water the bed the day before planting\n\nSTEP-BY-STEP PLANTING\n1. Soak spinach seeds in water for 12–24 hours before planting — this speeds germination\n2. Use a stick or finger to make furrows 1–2 cm deep, spaced 25–30 cm apart\n3. Drop seeds every 5 cm along each furrow\n4. Cover lightly with fine soil or compost and firm down gently\n5. Water with a fine spray — do not wash seeds away\n6. Germination takes 7–14 days\n7. When seedlings are 5 cm tall, thin to 15–20 cm apart — use thinned seedlings as baby spinach in salads\n8. For a continuous supply, sow a new row every 3 weeks (succession planting)\n\nWATERING SCHEDULE\nSeeds to germination: Keep soil consistently moist — water lightly every day\nEstablished plants: Water every 2 days in moderate weather, daily in hot or windy conditions\nAmount: Spinach has shallow roots — 2–3 litres per square metre is enough\nTechnique: Water at soil level, keep leaves dry to prevent fungal spots\nCritical: Never let the soil dry out completely — stressed spinach bolts prematurely\nMulch with straw to keep soil cool and retain moisture\n\nNURTURING YOUR PLANTS\nWeek 2: Apply 5 cm mulch of straw or grass clippings between rows\nWeek 3: Side-dress with a nitrogen-rich fertilizer — apply 30g of LAN per metre of row, spread 10 cm away from plants and water in\nEvery 2 weeks: Apply compost tea (soak compost in water for 48 hours, strain, and water plants) to encourage leaf growth\nWeekly: Remove any yellowing outer leaves to keep the plant productive\nWeekly: Check for and remove weeds — spinach does not compete well with weeds\n\nCOMMON PROBLEMS\n• Bolting (plants going to seed): Caused by heat or dry conditions — ensure adequate water and shade in warm weather\n• Downy mildew: Grey mould on leaf undersides in humid conditions — improve airflow, avoid wetting leaves\n• Leaf miners: Tunnels inside leaves from tiny flies — remove affected leaves, use row covers as prevention\n• Slugs: Holes in leaves, slime trails — set beer traps or scatter diatomaceous earth around plants\n\nHARVESTING\nSpinach can be harvested from 40 days after planting\n\nTwo harvesting methods:\n\nCut-and-come-again (recommended):\n1. Using scissors or a sharp knife, cut individual outer leaves 2–3 cm above the base\n2. Always leave the growing centre (at least 4–5 inner leaves) intact\n3. The plant will keep producing new leaves for 3–4 months this way\n4. Harvest every 5–7 days once established\n\nFull harvest:\n1. When the plant shows signs of bolting (centre stem rises, leaves become pointed), cut the whole plant at soil level\n2. The roots may re-sprout for a second smaller harvest\n\nHARVEST TIPS\n• Harvest in the morning when leaves are crisp and full of moisture\n• Young small leaves have the best flavour\n• Wash immediately after harvest and refrigerate in a damp cloth\n• Fresh spinach keeps for 5–7 days in the fridge\n• Excess spinach can be blanched and frozen for up to 6 months',
  30, 'en', true
),
(
  'Growing Potatoes: Complete Guide',
  'Step-by-step instructions for planting, hilling, watering, and harvesting potatoes in South Africa.',
  'Crops', 'beginner',
  E'Potatoes are a highly productive staple crop. A 10-metre row can yield 20–40 kg of potatoes, making them excellent value for small-scale farmers.\n\nBEST PLANTING SEASONS\nHighveld (Gauteng, Free State, North West): August–September (spring) and January–February (late summer)\nKwaZulu-Natal midlands: May–June and September–October\nWestern Cape: July–August (spring crop)\nAvoid frost — potatoes are damaged by frost, especially when young\n\nCHOOSING SEED POTATOES\n• Use certified disease-free seed potatoes from a reputable supplier\n• Choose varieties suited to your region: BP1, Mondial, Agria, or Sifra for most SA regions\n• Each seed potato should be roughly egg-sized (40–80g)\n• Larger potatoes can be cut into pieces — ensure each piece has at least 2 "eyes" (buds)\n• Allow cut pieces to dry and form a skin (callous) for 24–48 hours before planting\n\nSOIL PREPARATION\n1. Potatoes need deep, loose, well-drained soil — they cannot form well in compact or waterlogged soil\n2. Dig or till to 30–40 cm depth\n3. Remove all stones, clods, and weed roots\n4. Add 3–4 buckets of compost per square metre and mix in thoroughly\n5. Add 100g of superphosphate per square metre for root and tuber development\n6. Potatoes prefer slightly acidic soil: pH 5.5–6.0 — too much lime causes scab disease\n7. Form ridges 30 cm high and 60 cm apart using a hoe — potatoes grow in these ridges\n\nSTEP-BY-STEP PLANTING\n1. Using a hoe or trowel, make holes 15–20 cm deep along the ridge, spaced 30–35 cm apart\n2. Place one seed potato (eye facing up) in each hole\n3. Cover with 10–15 cm of soil — do not fill the hole completely yet\n4. Water gently — do not wash the seed potatoes out of position\n5. Mark rows with stakes so you know where plants will emerge\n6. Shoots emerge in 14–21 days depending on soil temperature\n7. When plants are 20 cm tall, perform first "hilling" (see Nurturing section)\n\nWATERING SCHEDULE\nPlanting to emergence: Keep soil just moist — not wet. Water every 3–4 days\nAfter emergence: Water every 3 days; increase to every 2 days in hot weather\nWhen flowering: This is the critical period — plants are forming tubers. Water consistently and deeply (5–8 litres per plant)\nAfter flowering subsides: Reduce watering gradually over 2–3 weeks as plants begin to die back\nLast 2 weeks before harvest: Stop watering completely — this hardens the potato skins for storage\nCritical: Inconsistent watering causes hollow heart (empty centres) and knobby, misshapen tubers\n\nNURTURING — HILLING IS ESSENTIAL\nHilling prevents tubers from being exposed to sunlight (which turns them green and toxic)\n\nFirst hilling — when plants are 20 cm tall:\n1. Use a hoe to mound soil up around the stems, leaving only the top 10 cm of leaves exposed\n2. This encourages more tubers to form along the buried stem\n3. Water after hilling\n\nSecond hilling — 3 weeks after first hilling:\n1. Mound soil again, burying another 10–15 cm of stem\n2. The ridges should now be 30–40 cm high\n3. Check that no tubers are poking out of the soil — cover any exposed ones immediately\n\nFERTILIZING\nAt planting: Superphosphate worked into the soil\n3 weeks after emergence: Side-dress with 3:2:1 fertilizer — apply 60g per metre of row, 15 cm from stems\nAt flowering: Apply potassium-rich fertilizer (3:1:5) to improve tuber size and quality\n\nDISEASE AND PEST WATCH\n• Late blight: Dark spots on leaves and stems in humid conditions — spray copper fungicide preventively; remove and burn affected plants\n• Potato tuber moth: Tunnels inside tubers — ensure tubers are well covered with soil, use pheromone traps\n• Aphids: Cluster under leaves — spray insecticidal soap\n• Common scab: Rough, corky patches on skin — caused by high pH, avoid over-liming\n\nHARVESTING\nEarly/new potatoes: 10–12 weeks after planting (small, tender, thin-skinned)\nMain crop potatoes: 16–20 weeks after planting\n\nSigns the crop is ready:\n• The foliage turns yellow and begins to die back and collapse\n• The skin of the potato does not rub off easily when pressed\n\nHow to harvest:\n1. Two weeks before harvesting, cut off all the above-ground foliage with shears\n2. Leave the tubers in the ground for 2 weeks — this hardens the skins for storage\n3. On harvest day, use a garden fork and insert it 30 cm from the plant base\n4. Lift the soil and gently pull the plant to reveal the potatoes\n5. Feel through the loosened soil with your hands to find all the tubers\n6. Do not pierce or cut tubers with the fork — damaged potatoes rot quickly\n7. Let potatoes dry on the soil surface for 2–3 hours if weather is dry\n\nSTORAGE\n• Store in a cool (7–10°C), dark, well-ventilated place — never in sunlight\n• Do NOT wash before storing — remove soil gently by hand\n• Store in hessian bags, wooden crates, or cardboard boxes — never airtight plastic\n• Check weekly and remove any rotting potatoes immediately to prevent spread\n• Properly stored potatoes keep for 3–6 months',
  50, 'en', true
),
(
  'Growing Carrots: Complete Guide',
  'Learn to plant, thin, water, and harvest carrots for crisp, sweet results in South African gardens.',
  'Crops', 'beginner',
  E'Carrots are a rewarding root vegetable that stores well and sells strongly. Success depends on correct soil preparation and consistent watering.\n\nBEST PLANTING SEASONS\nAll regions: March–May (autumn sowing for winter/spring crop) — this gives the sweetest carrots\nCooler regions (highveld, KZN midlands): August–September also works\nAvoid midsummer — germination is poor in heat and carrots become pithy\nCarrots take 70–90 days from sowing to harvest\n\nSOIL PREPARATION — THIS IS THE MOST CRITICAL STEP\nCarrots grow poorly in compacted, stony, or clay-heavy soils — they fork, twist, and stay small\n\n1. Choose a bed in full sun\n2. Dig deeply — 40–50 cm is ideal. Use a fork to break up subsoil\n3. Remove every stone, clod, and root fragment you can find\n4. Add 2 buckets of fine, well-rotted compost per square metre — avoid fresh manure (causes forked roots)\n5. Add 60g of superphosphate per square metre for root development\n6. Do NOT add nitrogen-heavy fertilizer at planting — this produces large leafy tops and small roots\n7. Rake the surface to a very fine, smooth texture — carrot seeds are tiny and need good seed-to-soil contact\n8. Water the prepared bed the day before sowing\n\nSTEP-BY-STEP PLANTING\nCarrot seeds are very small — sow directly into the bed, do not transplant\n\n1. Use a stick or the edge of a ruler to mark shallow furrows 1 cm deep, spaced 25 cm apart\n2. Mix carrot seeds with dry sand (1 part seed, 5 parts sand) — this helps spread the tiny seeds more evenly\n3. Sprinkle the seed-sand mixture thinly along the furrows\n4. Cover with a very thin layer of fine compost or fine soil (3–5 mm only — deeper burial prevents germination)\n5. Tamp gently with a flat board to ensure seed contact with soil\n6. Water very gently with a watering can fitted with a fine rose — do not wash seeds away\n7. Cover the bed with a light layer of dry grass mulch to retain moisture and prevent crusting\n8. Germination is slow: 14–21 days. Do not disturb the bed\n\nWATERING SCHEDULE\nSowing to germination: Water lightly every day — the top 3 cm of soil must never dry out\nAfter germination: Water every 2 days, wetting to 15–20 cm depth\nFrom 4 weeks onwards: Water every 3 days — deep watering (10–15 litres per square metre) encourages roots to grow downward\nCritical: Irregular watering (drying then flooding) causes carrot roots to crack and split\nIn dry, windy weather: Water daily to prevent surface crust forming over young seedlings\n\nTHINNING — DO NOT SKIP THIS STEP\nOvercrowded carrots produce stunted, twisted roots\n\nFirst thinning — when seedlings are 5 cm tall:\n1. Thin to one seedling every 3 cm by pulling out the extras at soil level\n2. Do this in the evening or on a cloudy day — carrot fly is attracted by the smell\n3. Remove thinnings from the area immediately — the smell attracts pests\n\nSecond thinning — when seedlings are 10 cm tall:\n1. Thin again to one every 6–8 cm\n2. The thinned-out seedlings can be eaten as baby carrots\n\nNURTURING\nWeek 2: Apply fine mulch between rows to retain moisture\nWeek 4: Side-dress with a balanced fertilizer (3:2:1) at 60g per metre of row — apply beside, not on, plants\nWeek 6: Check that carrot shoulders (tops of roots) are covered with soil — exposed tops turn green and bitter. Mound a little soil around any exposed tops\nWeekly: Remove weeds by hand — be careful not to disturb carrot roots\n\nHARVESTING\nCarrots are ready 70–90 days after sowing\n\nSigns of readiness:\n• The top of the root at soil level is 1.5–2.5 cm in diameter (for most varieties)\n• The shoulders of the carrot push slightly above the soil surface\n• Check by gently pulling one test carrot\n\nHow to harvest:\n1. Water the bed well 1–2 hours before harvesting — this loosens the soil\n2. Insert a garden fork 10 cm beside the row and gently lever upward\n3. Grasp the foliage close to the root and ease the carrot out — pulling tops alone can break the root\n4. For very deep or firm soil, loosen along the entire row before pulling\n\nAFTER HARVEST\n1. Twist or cut off the foliage immediately — leaves draw moisture from the root\n2. Do not wash before storing\n3. Store in a cool, dark place in damp sand or sawdust — this keeps carrots crisp for weeks\n4. Refrigerated in a plastic bag with small holes: keeps for 3–4 weeks\n5. For market: Grade by size, bundle in 500g–1 kg bundles, keep cool and misted',
  40, 'en', true
),
(
  'Growing Onions: Complete Guide',
  'Complete step-by-step instructions for raising, transplanting, watering, and curing onions in South Africa.',
  'Crops', 'intermediate',
  E'Onions are a high-value crop that stores for months and is in constant demand. They require patience — 5 months from seed to harvest — but reward the effort greatly.\n\nBEST PLANTING SEASONS\nHighveld regions: Sow seeds in seedbed: March–April. Transplant: May–June. Harvest: October–November\nKwaZulu-Natal and Eastern Cape: Sow: February–March. Transplant: April. Harvest: September–October\nWestern Cape: Sow: January–March. Transplant: March–April. Harvest: August–September\nOnion bulb formation is triggered by day-length — plant at the right time for your latitude\n\nSOIL PREPARATION\n1. Choose a sunny, open spot with excellent drainage — onions rot in wet soil\n2. Dig to 25–30 cm depth, break up all clods\n3. Onions need fertile soil: add 3 buckets of compost per square metre\n4. Add 80g of 2:3:2 fertilizer per square metre and work in thoroughly\n5. Target pH 6.0–7.0 — test and adjust before planting\n6. Form raised beds 20 cm high for excellent drainage\n7. Rake to a fine, flat surface\n\nSTEP-BY-STEP — RAISING SEEDLINGS (weeks 1–8)\n1. Fill seed trays with fine seedling mix\n2. Sow seeds 5 mm deep, roughly 1 cm apart\n3. Water gently and keep in a warm sheltered location (15–20°C)\n4. Germination takes 10–14 days — keep moist throughout\n5. After germination, move to full sun and water daily\n6. After 6 weeks, trim the green tops of seedlings to 8–10 cm with scissors — this toughens them and stimulates root development. Repeat once more at week 8\n7. Seedlings are ready to transplant when they are pencil-thick and 15–20 cm tall (about 8–10 weeks)\n\nSTEP-BY-STEP TRANSPLANTING (week 8–10)\n1. Water the seedbed well the evening before transplanting\n2. Pull seedlings carefully, keeping roots intact\n3. Trim roots to 5 cm and trim tops to 12–15 cm — this reduces transplant shock\n4. In the prepared bed, make holes with a dibber or stick 8–10 cm deep, spaced 10 cm apart in rows 25–30 cm apart\n5. Lower each seedling in so the root is fully buried but the base of the plant (the slight swelling where root meets stem) is only 1–2 cm below the surface — planting too deep produces poor bulbs\n6. Firm soil around each seedling and water immediately\n7. Shade lightly with shade cloth for 3–5 days after transplanting to reduce stress\n\nWATERING SCHEDULE\nAfter transplanting — week 1–2: Water every day to help plants establish\nWeeks 3–10: Water every 2–3 days. Onions need consistent moisture but dislike wet feet\nBulbing stage (from week 12 onwards, when tops start to thicken at base): Reduce watering to every 4–5 days — too much water at this stage dilutes flavor and promotes disease\nFinal 2 weeks before harvest: Stop all watering — this is critical for neck drying and good storage life\nAmount: 5–8 litres per square metre per watering, applied slowly\n\nNURTURING\nWeek 3: Apply 5 cm mulch between rows (avoid touching stems)\nWeek 4: Side-dress with nitrogen fertilizer (LAN at 60g per 5-metre row) — apply beside plants, not on them, and water in. This promotes green, leafy growth\nWeek 8: Second nitrogen application at same rate\nWeek 12 (as bulbs form): Apply potassium-rich fertilizer (3:1:5) to improve bulb size and storage quality. Stop all nitrogen now — late nitrogen makes necks thick and causes poor curing\nWeekly: Hand-weed between rows — onion roots are shallow and do not compete well with weeds\n\nDISEASE WATCH\n• Purple blotch: Purple spots on leaves in humid conditions — spray copper fungicide, avoid overhead watering\n• Downy mildew: Grey, fluffy growth on leaves — improve airflow, spray mancozeb\n• Neck rot: Affects stored onions — cause is wet necks at harvest, ensure correct curing\n• Thrips: Silvery streaks on leaves — spray with spinosad or neem oil\n\nHARVESTING\nOnions are ready approximately 5 months after transplanting\n\nSigns of readiness:\n• 50–70% of the green tops have fallen over naturally — do NOT force them over\n• The neck (just above the bulb) feels soft and thin\n• The outer skin has turned papery and brown\n\nHow to harvest:\n1. On a dry, sunny day, use a fork to loosen the soil beneath the bulbs\n2. Pull bulbs out and lay them on top of the soil or on wire mesh raised off the ground\n3. Leave them in the field or a well-ventilated, shaded area for 2–3 weeks to CURE\n4. Curing: The outer skins dry and shrink, the neck seals completely, preserving the bulb\n5. Good curing is the key to long storage life\n\nSTORAGE AFTER CURING\n• Trim roots and cut tops to 2 cm above the bulb\n• Store in mesh bags, crates, or plaited bundles in a cool, dry, well-ventilated place\n• Do not store in plastic bags — onions need airflow\n• Properly cured and stored onions keep for 6–8 months\n• Check monthly and remove any that are softening',
  55, 'en', true
),
(
  'Growing Butternut Squash: Complete Guide',
  'How to plant, train, water, and harvest butternut squash for excellent yield and quality.',
  'Crops', 'beginner',
  E'Butternut squash is a fast-growing, high-yielding crop that thrives in the South African summer. Each plant can produce 6–12 large fruits weighing 1–2 kg each.\n\nBEST PLANTING SEASONS\nAll summer-rainfall regions: September–November (spring/early summer)\nWestern Cape: September–October\nKZN coast: August–October\nButternut is frost-sensitive — do not plant until all frost risk has passed\nCrop matures in 80–100 days from planting\n\nSOIL PREPARATION\n1. Choose a sunny spot with full sun all day — butternut needs heat to produce well\n2. Dig planting holes 60 cm wide and 40 cm deep, spaced 1.5 m apart (butternut vines spread widely)\n3. Fill each hole with a mix of: equal parts soil, compost, and kraal manure\n4. Add one tablespoon of superphosphate to each hole and mix in\n5. Mound the mixture into a slight hill or "kopje" 15 cm above ground level — this is your planting mound\n6. Water the mounds well and let settle for a few days before planting\n\nSTEP-BY-STEP PLANTING\n1. Sow seeds directly into the mound or start in seed trays 3–4 weeks earlier\n2. If direct sowing: Push 3 seeds 2–3 cm deep into each mound, spaced in a triangle\n3. Water gently after sowing\n4. Germination: 7–10 days\n5. When seedlings have 2 true leaves (2–3 weeks after emergence), thin to the strongest 1–2 plants per mound\n6. If transplanting from trays: Transplant when seedlings have 2–3 true leaves. Handle roots gently — squash dislikes root disturbance\n7. Water well immediately after planting and shade for 2–3 days if very hot\n\nWATERING SCHEDULE\nSowing to germination: Keep mound moist, water every 1–2 days\nYoung plants (weeks 1–4): Water deeply every 2–3 days — apply 5–8 litres per plant\nFlowering and fruit set (weeks 5–8): Water deeply every 2–3 days consistently — irregular water causes fruit drop and poor shape\nFruit development (weeks 8–12): Continue regular watering — 10–15 litres per plant per session\nFinal 2 weeks before harvest: Reduce watering to harden the skin\nTechnique: Water at the base of the plant — wet leaves encourage powdery mildew\n\nNURTURING\nWeek 2: Mulch heavily around the mound and along where vines will spread (newspaper + straw works well)\nWeek 3: Side-dress with balanced fertilizer (3:2:1) at 100g per plant — apply in a ring 30 cm from the stem\nWeek 4: Begin training the main vine in the direction you want it to grow — gently redirect if needed\nWeek 5 onwards: When flowers appear, you will see male and female flowers. Female flowers have a small swelling (baby fruit) at their base\nPollination: In the morning, use a small paintbrush or your finger to transfer pollen from male flowers to the centre of female flowers. This improves fruit set, especially in areas with few bees\nWeek 6: When small fruits are 5 cm long, remove all but 4–6 fruits per plant — this directs energy to producing larger, better quality fruit\nWeek 7: Side-dress again with potassium-rich fertilizer (3:1:5) to improve fruit quality and skin hardness\n\nDISEASE AND PEST WATCH\n• Powdery mildew: White powdery coating on leaves — usually appears later in the season. Spray with bicarbonate of soda solution (5g per litre) or sulfur-based fungicide\n• Squash borer: Wilting vine despite good water — check base of stem for entry hole and frass (sawdust-like material). Inject Bt into the hole or cut out the borer with a knife and bury the stem section\n• Aphids: Cluster on new growth — spray insecticidal soap\n• Cucumber mosaic virus: Mottled, distorted leaves — remove and destroy plant, control aphids which spread the virus\n\nHARVESTING\nButternut is ready 80–100 days after planting\n\nSigns of readiness:\n• The skin changes from shiny green to a dull beige/tan colour — this is the most reliable sign\n• The skin is hard and cannot be scratched with a fingernail\n• The stem attached to the fruit starts to dry, harden, and turn corky\n• Tap the fruit — a hollow sound indicates ripeness\n\nHow to harvest:\n1. Use sharp secateurs or a knife to cut the stem 5–8 cm above the fruit — do not break or pull off the stem\n2. A long stem (5 cm) prevents the entry point from rotting in storage\n3. Handle carefully — bruised fruit rots quickly in storage\n4. Leave the harvested fruit in the sun for 10–14 days to CURE — this hardens the skin further and extends storage life\n\nSTORAGE\n• After curing, store in a cool, dry place with good airflow\n• Do NOT refrigerate uncured or whole butternut\n• Whole, properly cured butternut stores for 3–6 months\n• Once cut, wrap in plastic and refrigerate — use within 5 days',
  40, 'en', true
),
(
  'Growing Mangoes: Complete Guide',
  'From young tree establishment to first harvest — a complete mango-growing guide for South African farmers.',
  'Crops', 'intermediate',
  E'Mangoes are a profitable, long-term investment. A healthy mango tree can produce fruit for 40+ years and yield 100–300 kg per season at full maturity. Limpopo, Mpumalanga, and the KZN north coast are ideal regions.\n\nBEST REGIONS AND CLIMATE\n• Ideal: Hot, dry winters and hot, humid summers — Limpopo and Mpumalanga lowveld\n• Suitable: Northern KZN coast, parts of Eastern Cape coast\n• Not suitable: Highveld, Western Cape (too cold), high-rainfall coastal areas (encourages anthracnose disease)\n• Mangoes need a dry, cool period (15–20°C) of 2–3 months in winter to trigger flowering\n• Temperature below 4°C damages flowers and young fruit\n\nCHOOSING VARIETIES\nFor South Africa, the best commercial varieties are:\n• Tommy Atkins — red-flushed, excellent for export, firm, fibreless\n• Kent — large, sweet, low fibre, good shelf life\n• Sensation — red-green, good flavour, popular locally\n• Keitt — late-season variety, large, sweet\n• Buy grafted trees from a certified nursery — grafted trees fruit in 3–5 years vs 6–8 years for seedlings\n\nPLANTING SITE AND SOIL PREPARATION\n1. Choose a north-facing slope with full sun and good cold air drainage (cold air settles in hollows during winter)\n2. Mangoes need deep, well-drained soil (at least 1.5 m deep) — they do not tolerate waterlogging\n3. Sandy loam to clay loam soils are ideal\n4. Mark out planting positions: 8 m × 8 m spacing for full orchards; 6 m × 8 m for higher-density planting\n5. Dig planting holes 1 m wide and 1 m deep at least 4–6 weeks before planting\n6. Mix removed soil with equal parts compost and fill back into the hole, mounding slightly\n7. Add 200g superphosphate and 200g agricultural lime to each hole and mix in\n8. Let the hole settle and re-mound after rain\n\nSTEP-BY-STEP PLANTING (young grafted trees)\n1. Best planting time: October–November (start of rainy season) so the tree benefits from summer rains\n2. Water the nursery tree well 24 hours before planting\n3. Dig a hole in the centre of your prepared mound just large enough to fit the root ball\n4. Carefully remove the nursery bag without disturbing the root ball\n5. Place the tree in the hole so the graft union (the slight bend or bump near the base of the trunk) is 10–15 cm ABOVE the soil surface — burying the graft union causes rootstock growth\n6. Backfill with the prepared soil mix and firm in gently\n7. Build a small basin (ring of soil) around the tree 30–40 cm from the trunk to capture water\n8. Water slowly with 20–30 litres per tree\n9. Apply a 10 cm layer of mulch in the basin, keeping it 10 cm away from the trunk\n10. Install a stake and tie the young tree for support against wind\n\nWATERING SCHEDULE\nYear 1 (establishment): Water every 3–5 days during the dry season — the tree cannot yet access deep soil moisture. Apply 20–30 litres per tree per watering\nYear 2: Water every 5–7 days during dry spells\nYear 3 onwards: Mature trees can survive on rainfall alone in good rainfall areas (600mm+). Irrigate in dry spells, especially during fruit development\nCritical water timings:\n• After planting and throughout first year\n• During flowering (do NOT irrigate heavily — dry conditions encourage flowering)\n• After fruit set: Water consistently to prevent fruit drop\n• During fruit swelling (30–60 days before harvest): Regular irrigation increases fruit size significantly\n• Stop irrigating 2–3 weeks before harvest to improve flavour and sugar content\n\nFERTILIZING PROGRAMME\nYear 1: Every 3 months, apply 100g of balanced fertilizer (3:2:1 or 2:3:2) in a ring 30 cm from trunk\nYear 2: 200g every 3 months\nYear 3+: Apply fertilizer after harvest and again before flowering:\n• Post-harvest (April–May): High-nitrogen fertilizer to promote new growth — 300g LAN per tree\n• Pre-flowering (July–August): High-potassium fertilizer (3:1:5) — 200g per tree to encourage flowering and fruit quality\n• At fruit set: Balanced fertilizer 200g per tree\n\nNURTURING THE ORCHARD\nPruning Year 1–3:\n1. After planting, prune the central leader at 60–80 cm height to encourage branching\n2. In year 2, select 3–4 strong, well-spaced branches as the main scaffold branches, remove the rest\n3. These pruning decisions shape the tree structure for the next 40 years\n\nAnnual pruning (after each harvest):\n1. Remove dead, crossing, or inward-growing branches\n2. Trim the canopy to keep trees manageable and to allow light and spray coverage into the centre\n3. Remove any rootstock shoots growing from below the graft union immediately\n\nDISEASE AND PEST MANAGEMENT\n• Anthracnose: Most important mango disease — black spots on flowers, fruit, and leaves. Spray copper fungicide or mancozeb from bud burst through fruit development. Prune for good airflow\n• Powdery mildew: White coating on flowers — spray sulfur fungicide before and during flowering\n• Mango seed weevil: Larvae develop inside the seed — difficult to control; use certified clean budwood for grafting\n• Mango fruit fly: Lays eggs in ripening fruit — use protein bait traps, pick up fallen fruit daily\n• Scale insects: Brown scales on stems — spray with white oil\n\nHARVESTING\nGrafted trees begin bearing in years 3–5. Full production from year 7–10 onwards\n\nMaturity indicators:\n• Skin colour changes: some varieties develop red blush; all varieties lose the bright green colour\n• Shoulders of the fruit (around the stem) become rounded and full — early-season fruit has flat shoulders\n• A few fruit drop naturally — pick up and cut open to assess internal colour (the flesh turns yellow)\n• Mature fruit floats in water; immature fruit sinks\n\nHow to harvest:\n1. Harvest in the cool of the morning\n2. Use a picking pole with a bag or basket — avoid dropping fruit, bruising causes rapid rotting\n3. Cut the stalk 5–8 cm from the fruit — this prevents "sap burn" (sap dripping onto fruit skin causes black marks)\n4. After cutting, hold fruit stalk-end DOWN to allow sap to drain before placing in crates\n5. Place (do not throw) fruit into lined crates — one layer deep to prevent bruising\n6. Move to shade immediately\n\nPOST-HARVEST\n• Hot water treatment (HWT): Dip fruit in water at 52°C for 5 minutes — kills fruit fly eggs and reduces anthracnose\n• Grade by size and quality for market\n• Store at 12–13°C for up to 3 weeks\n• Ripen at room temperature (20–25°C) — takes 4–7 days after harvest',
  60, 'en', true
),
(
  'Growing Cabbage: Complete Guide',
  'Step-by-step guide to raising, transplanting, feeding, and harvesting firm, quality cabbage heads.',
  'Crops', 'beginner',
  E'Cabbage is a consistent, reliable vegetable crop that handles cool temperatures well and produces heavy heads that sell well at markets and to retailers.\n\nBEST PLANTING SEASONS\nSummer rainfall regions (highveld): Main season: transplant March–May for winter crop; also September for summer crop\nKZN and Eastern Cape: Transplant April–June and August–October\nWestern Cape: Transplant March–May (for winter/spring harvest)\nCabbage grows best at 15–20°C and tolerates light frost\nDays to harvest: 60–90 days after transplanting depending on variety\n\nCHOOSING A VARIETY\n• Round head types: Star 3301, Conquistador, Grandslam — most common in South Africa, firm heads, good shelf life\n• Flat/Drumhead types: Larger heads, good for fresh markets\n• Red cabbage: Niche product, premium price, fewer pests\n• Buy fresh, certified seed from a reputable seed company each season\n\nSOIL PREPARATION\n1. Select a site in full sun\n2. Dig to 25–30 cm depth and remove all previous crop debris\n3. Cabbage is a heavy feeder: add 3–4 buckets of compost per square metre\n4. Add 100g of 2:3:2 fertilizer per square metre and work in well\n5. Aim for pH 6.5–7.0. Cabbage is susceptible to clubroot in acidic soils — add lime if pH is below 6.5\n6. Rake smooth and form a level, fine-textured seedbed\n7. Water well and allow to settle 2–3 days before transplanting\n\nRAISING SEEDLINGS (weeks 1–5)\n1. Fill seed trays with fine seedling mix\n2. Sow 2–3 seeds per cell, 5 mm deep\n3. Water and keep at 15–20°C — germination takes 5–8 days\n4. Thin to 1 seedling per cell once the first true leaf appears\n5. Keep seedlings in full sun and water daily\n6. At week 3, water with a dilute liquid fertilizer (half-strength 2:3:2 dissolved in water) to strengthen seedlings\n7. Begin hardening off at week 4: place outside in afternoon shade, then full sun\n8. Seedlings are ready to transplant when they have 4–5 true leaves (5–6 weeks old)\n\nSTEP-BY-STEP TRANSPLANTING\n1. Transplant in the late afternoon or on a cool, cloudy day to reduce transplant shock\n2. Water seedlings thoroughly 1 hour before transplanting\n3. Spacing: 40–45 cm between plants, 50–60 cm between rows\n4. Dig holes just large enough for the root ball\n5. Plant at the same depth the seedling was growing in the tray — do not plant too deep\n6. Firm soil around the stem and water immediately with 500 ml per plant\n7. If very sunny, shade with cut branches or shade cloth for 3–4 days\n\nWATERING SCHEDULE\nWeeks 1–2 after transplanting: Water every day — small amounts to keep soil moist\nWeeks 3–6: Water every 2 days, applying 3–5 litres per plant\nFrom week 6 as heads begin to form: Water every 2–3 days very consistently — irregular watering causes heads to split\nAmount: 4–6 litres per plant per watering, applied slowly at the base\nCritical: As heads reach full size, sudden heavy watering after a dry spell causes rapid expansion and splitting — maintain consistency\nAvoid: Overhead watering once heads begin to form — water trapped in the head causes inner rot\n\nNURTURING\nWeek 2: Apply 5 cm mulch between rows — keeps moisture in and weeds down\nWeek 3: Side-dress with nitrogen fertilizer (LAN at 60g per metre of row) — apply beside the row, 10 cm from plants, water in well\nWeek 5: Second nitrogen application at same rate\nWeek 7: Apply potassium fertilizer (3:1:5) as heads form to improve firmness and quality. Stop nitrogen at this point\nWeekly: Inspect the outer leaves and remove any heavily pest-damaged leaves to improve airflow\nWeekly: Hand-weed between rows — cabbages cannot compete well with weeds\n\nPEST AND DISEASE MANAGEMENT\n• Diamondback moth (DBM): Small green caterpillars creating windows in leaves — the most damaging cabbage pest. Spray with Bt (Bacillus thuringiensis) or spinosad. Rotate chemical classes to prevent resistance\n• Cabbage looper: Large, looping caterpillar — hand-pick early, spray Bt\n• Aphids: Grey clusters under leaves and in heads — spray insecticidal soap or use ladybird releases\n• Clubroot: Swollen, distorted roots, wilting plants — caused by soil fungus in acidic conditions. No chemical cure — apply lime to raise pH and avoid replanting brassicas for 6+ years\n• Black rot: Yellow V-shaped lesions on leaf edges — caused by wet conditions and poor airflow. Remove affected leaves, spray copper fungicide\n\nHARVESTING\nCabbage heads are ready 60–90 days after transplanting\n\nSigns of readiness:\n• The head feels firm and solid when squeezed — like a softball\n• The head has reached the expected size for the variety (1–2 kg typically)\n• The outer leaves begin to curl slightly outward\n• Do not wait too long — overripe heads split open, losing market value\n\nHow to harvest:\n1. In the morning when it is cool\n2. With a sharp knife, cut the head from the stem, leaving 3–4 outer wrapper leaves attached to protect the head\n3. Leave the root and stem in the ground — secondary side-heads often develop and can be harvested 3–4 weeks later as smaller but still valuable "baby cabbages"\n4. Grade heads by size and firmness\n\nSTORAGE AND HANDLING\n• Fresh-cut cabbages keep in a cool, shaded place for up to 2 weeks\n• Do not wash before storage — moisture promotes rot\n• For market: Do not remove the outer wrapper leaves — they protect the head during transport\n• Refrigerated: Whole heads keep for 3–5 weeks at 0–4°C\n• Excess production: Ferment as sauerkraut or kimchi for value-added product',
  42, 'en', true
)
ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;


